00:00:00.170 --> 00:00:02.950
My name is Bill Durham. I'm Bing Professor in

00:00:02.950 --> 00:00:07.130
Human Biology and Human Biology and Anthropology at Stanford University.

00:00:07.130 --> 00:00:11.760
&gt;&gt; Well, we're really happy you're joining us especially to talk about a

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:13.950
very important concept. Now, we've been

00:00:13.950 --> 00:00:16.840
learning about lactose intolerance and about the

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:21.110
idea that as all infants. We have the ability as mammals to digest

00:00:21.110 --> 00:00:23.460
these lactose containing products. And as

00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:26.320
we get older our lactate expression diminishes.

00:00:26.320 --> 00:00:29.400
But in some people, the lactate gene sort of stays

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.900
on, and we continue to make lactates. And so we'll

00:00:31.900 --> 00:00:35.470
start of by asking why in human evolution would something

00:00:35.470 --> 00:00:38.900
like this happen? How could something like this even happen?

00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:41.920
&gt;&gt; Well, from a pan-mammalian background where the

00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:45.840
lactase activity peaks around birth and then tails

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:48.410
off quickly into the weaning period and into

00:00:48.410 --> 00:00:51.280
adulthood. We assume, we know that that's pan-mammalian.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:54.880
Even your house cat is lactose malabsorbed. A malabsorber

00:00:54.880 --> 00:00:58.910
or lactose intolerant. at least every house cat that's

00:00:58.910 --> 00:01:01.650
been tested is. Eve, even those people will give

00:01:01.650 --> 00:01:05.040
milk to their house cats. And what we don't know

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:07.040
is whether the people have found the threshold or

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:08.830
the cat's found the threshold to avoid diarrhea and

00:01:08.830 --> 00:01:12.900
other consequences. What's interesting then is from that background

00:01:12.900 --> 00:01:16.690
of a peak, some human populations show persistent lactase activity,

00:01:16.690 --> 00:01:19.380
into adulthood. While the majority continue to

00:01:19.380 --> 00:01:22.940
decline. So it's that minority of lactose

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:26.590
tolerant adults that are really fascinating. It's

00:01:26.590 --> 00:01:28.430
a wonderful question because here's a case where

00:01:28.430 --> 00:01:31.160
you have interest specific polymorphism. You have

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:36.030
existence and if the ongoing persistence of a

00:01:36.030 --> 00:01:39.450
genetic difference between human populations. With regard

00:01:39.450 --> 00:01:41.970
to some relatively simple trait and a trait

00:01:41.970 --> 00:01:45.030
that has to be relatively recent in human history.

00:01:45.030 --> 00:01:45.590
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:01:45.590 --> 00:01:48.185
&gt;&gt; There were no sources of milk prior to dairy

00:01:48.185 --> 00:01:50.780
animals. So what we have here is, I mean other

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:53.160
than mother's milk there were no mammalian sources of milk

00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:56.800
for human population before agriculture and so here we have.

00:01:56.800 --> 00:01:58.250
&gt;&gt; Right, there's this, right, I was going

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:00.360
to wonder too, you know, the idea that. I

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:02.050
mean, are we the only species that actually

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:04.890
drinks the milk from another species as, as well?

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:07.780
&gt;&gt; I'm not aware of any species that makes

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:14.520
a habit of drinking the milk of another species. I'm aware of infants of,

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:20.740
a particular, an infant of a particular mother, nursing from

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:25.430
another mother. That happens in pinnipeds; it happens in several mammals. It's

00:02:25.430 --> 00:02:29.970
considered milk stealing. and obviously, there's

00:02:29.970 --> 00:02:32.770
great reward to the successful pup, but,

00:02:32.770 --> 00:02:35.850
I'm not aware of another case where, especially,

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:38.650
where infants or adults drink milk from another

00:02:38.650 --> 00:02:41.394
mammal. That's a, that's a good question, I

00:02:41.394 --> 00:02:44.460
really don't, just don't know an answer to that.

00:02:44.460 --> 00:02:48.090
&gt;&gt; so we have this scenario then as you mention where we have this sort of

00:02:48.090 --> 00:02:50.870
minority of people who, instead of having lactase

00:02:50.870 --> 00:02:53.550
expression diminish over time it's, it's, it's persistent lactase.

00:02:53.550 --> 00:02:55.492
&gt;&gt; Persistent lactase activity into adulthood. Uh-huh.

00:02:55.492 --> 00:02:58.190
&gt;&gt; Sure. Now, you mention that it seems to be relevant

00:02:58.190 --> 00:03:02.370
specifically because of the recent evolution of this trait.

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:02.400
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:04.830
&gt;&gt; Because the domestication of dairy.

00:03:04.830 --> 00:03:05.443
&gt;&gt; Uh-huh.

00:03:05.443 --> 00:03:05.760
&gt;&gt;

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:09.170
&gt;&gt; So we assume that the pan-mammalian background means that at the dawn

00:03:09.170 --> 00:03:12.030
of history human populations were all

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:15.600
lactose intolerant. And that there would be

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.560
at best a mutationally low frequency

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:20.140
of individuals that varied on that characteristic.

00:03:20.140 --> 00:03:23.330
And because it was a very low variation, and there was no milk

00:03:23.330 --> 00:03:24.940
available, we would have no way of knowing how

00:03:24.940 --> 00:03:26.580
much there was, or how often it recurred and

00:03:26.580 --> 00:03:29.650
so on. But what we have then in the

00:03:29.650 --> 00:03:34.570
meantime is this great invention called agriculture. The domestication of

00:03:34.570 --> 00:03:37.140
plants and animals at the service of the human

00:03:37.140 --> 00:03:41.400
food supply. We have every reason to believe that the

00:03:41.400 --> 00:03:43.640
main animals that are used for milk today, were

00:03:43.640 --> 00:03:48.200
originally domesticated for meat. They were valued first for meat,

00:03:48.200 --> 00:03:51.070
and that milk was as the, expression goes,

00:03:51.070 --> 00:03:53.730
were part of a secondary products revolution. Where

00:03:53.730 --> 00:03:56.130
they realized that you could use more than

00:03:56.130 --> 00:03:59.540
the meat from these animals, goats, sheep, you

00:03:59.540 --> 00:04:02.210
know, cattle and so on. And so, they

00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:04.796
already probably had them in close association with

00:04:04.796 --> 00:04:08.160
human communities, they were probably already harvesting the

00:04:08.160 --> 00:04:12.910
meat regularly. They probably had mastered overwintering, water supply,

00:04:12.910 --> 00:04:16.000
herding activities, and that sort of thing. And

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.540
then suddenly there's evidence for using the, the

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:22.840
milk product of these animals. some of the

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:26.020
earliest evidence comes from Sahara rock paintings that

00:04:26.020 --> 00:04:29.410
are dated to 4500 B.P. that show, in

00:04:29.410 --> 00:04:32.950
fact, bringing the calf up, near the female,

00:04:32.950 --> 00:04:35.810
the adult female. And human being underneath. Now

00:04:35.810 --> 00:04:38.050
we infer that the human being underneath is doing

00:04:38.050 --> 00:04:40.255
this, what else is a human being doing under a cow?

00:04:40.255 --> 00:04:41.255
&gt;&gt;

00:04:40.255 --> 00:04:41.533
[LAUGH]

00:04:41.533 --> 00:04:43.530
&gt;&gt; But that's some of the earliest

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:45.330
evidence, and what's interesting is that they bring

00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:50.340
the calf up, to trigger the letdown reflex in the, in the cow so that

00:04:50.340 --> 00:04:53.830
the humans can take the milk. And to this day, farmers will tell you, there's

00:04:53.830 --> 00:04:57.220
lot of ways to induce that reflex. But one of them is bringing the calf up.

00:04:57.220 --> 00:04:58.587
&gt;&gt; That makes so much sense.

00:04:58.587 --> 00:04:59.587
&gt;&gt;

00:04:58.587 --> 00:04:58.780
[INAUDIBLE].

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:01.800
&gt;&gt; It's like a woman hearing a baby cry in a department store.

00:05:01.800 --> 00:05:02.450
&gt;&gt; Absolutely, yeah.

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:03.440
&gt;&gt; And she starts lactating.

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:05.860
&gt;&gt; huh, yep. Absolutely, same thing. And

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:09.560
so, It's clear, then. Or we surmise, from

00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:11.660
this history, that, milk was valued. Or that

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:13.900
cattle were valued first. For beef, or for

00:05:13.900 --> 00:05:15.930
their meat product, and then later for

00:05:15.930 --> 00:05:18.580
milk. Milk was a secondary product. It wasn't

00:05:18.580 --> 00:05:21.110
very effective. And the question then became, well

00:05:21.110 --> 00:05:23.800
what was the advantage of milk on top

00:05:23.800 --> 00:05:25.460
of the meat? If you've already got an addition

00:05:25.460 --> 00:05:27.620
to your food supply, why is it that milk suddenly

00:05:27.620 --> 00:05:30.680
is valuable? That's triggered the most debate and the, and

00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:34.230
the most interesting research, I think. now the question really

00:05:34.230 --> 00:05:37.640
was, what was the added value. Of drinking fresh milk?

00:05:38.770 --> 00:05:41.260
It's complicated on the one hand, because you had the

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:45.550
meat value of these animals you domesticated. So, it seems

00:05:45.550 --> 00:05:49.990
unlikely that it would be just protein or food supply,

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:52.620
yet that was an important early argument. And

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:55.400
the question, and, and, it's also complicated because

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:02.960
There are ways to get some food value from milk without drinking it fresh. You

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:09.740
can all societies that I know of have ways of processing fresh milk.

00:06:09.740 --> 00:06:16.250
Into low lactose forms. Sour milk is a low lactose form. All the things like

00:06:16.250 --> 00:06:20.440
yogurt and kefir. Drinks that are widely known in some places. And most cheeses.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:20.940
&gt;&gt; Mm hm.

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:22.930
&gt;&gt; Break down the lactose

00:06:22.930 --> 00:06:28.500
externally, using lactobacillus bacteria. Using a separation of curds and whey.

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:32.370
Lactose is water soluble. It drains off with the whey, and the

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:37.030
curds are free of lactose. So most cheeses have very little

00:06:37.030 --> 00:06:40.540
lactose concentration, something like yogurt is

00:06:40.540 --> 00:06:43.190
full of lactobacillus that's already digesting

00:06:43.190 --> 00:06:43.600
&gt;&gt; Sure.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:47.149
&gt;&gt; The lactose for human consumption. So here's the real challenge.

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:55.000
In a world where most populations. Huh, sorry. In a world where most populations

